{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Buildings{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Wentworth Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, E1.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 It was these actual buildings here was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, when Hackney House you see - was built so we had to come out of there, you see, so I was - away two - another building about six weeks, but I came back in six weeks. So I moved into 77 College Buildings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What was the first number?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Thirty-one. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 And you lived there right through?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
I lived there sixty-three years. And I've lived here in 77 College Buildings near on four years. Come December.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you've lived in this particular block all your life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 The whole of - all my life, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 None.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 There was just you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 That's all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where did your father come from did he come from round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He came round - from Old Montague S
treet. It - it's in Casson Street, you know, on Montague Street, now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Is that off the Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes - down that way. Number 14. No it wasn't - \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 - George Street. That's right, 14 George Street, near Blackline Yard, opposite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What was his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
He was a - a - when he got - before he got married to my mother - he was a feather maker. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was that for pillows and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, for hats. Years ago, yes. Yes. And he worked in Clerkenwell but whereabouts I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Then you say he became a milkman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. He married my mother - and he went to work for my uncle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was your uncle on your mother's side?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. My mother's side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where did your mother come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I - she worked in the da
iry, my own mother, I've been told, but I don't remember my mother - too much, 'cos I was rather young. In 1904 - she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your father marry again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. A year after. In 1905. And he got married at Springfield's church.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do you remember whether your father had any other job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, nothing else he had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He was a milkman all his life from then on was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 That's right, he was a milkman, and also a feather maker. And dyer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 But most of the time you were a child he was a milkman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He was a milkman. YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What did this involve for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well it made no difference, I suppose really - meeting my mother - and my uncle - I suppose they got attached to one another and that's why he went in and worked, and - my father got married - to Rose Burrough, her name was. But I don't remember her much.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do you remember your step-mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
I remember - I remember me step-mother well. They got married in 1905. Like my mother - step-mother died in 1930. Yes. And there was no children, only - there was only me, by my own mother. And I had a happy life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How old was your father and mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well I - to - correctly - my father was seventy-two when he died, and - 1939 my father died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you were born in 1898 so that would be forty-one years off seventy-three?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
He'd be over a hundred by now. If he was alive now. Thirty-three years he's been dead. And he was seventy-three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 That makes him thirty-two when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How about your mother, was she about the same age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
My mother - I can't say when she was born, but she died when she was thirty-six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So she'd be twenty-eight when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. No, no, I was born 1898.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So she'd be thirty when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you too young to remember the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, I don't remember my - own mother's funeral. But I remember my - step-mother's. That was in 1930.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have many relatives living round this area, your mother and father'
s own relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. Only my uncle who my father worked for. But I had a - a couple of aunts round here. Near the milk shop. That was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you see much of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I see nothing of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Not even in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. No, 
I haven't seen my relatives now for about fifty odd years. But I've got a cousin come up - about a year ago, but - that's after fifty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you didn't have that many relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh no, no, only - my uncle who my father worked for. And my aunt
 Emily. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did they come round very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, they - no. Unless we saw them in the road, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Do you remember how many rooms there were in the house in 81 College Buildings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How many I had? Two rooms. And we used to pay four and six a week for rent.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 Was that run by Ty}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 nby Hall then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You know where Atlee House is? There. On the first landing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was that still owned by Tynby Hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, we come under them - a few years now. But it was - the name of - 
oh what is his name now - it's in his name here - wait a minute - no. Oh, Mr Lawson. Harry Lawson his name was, he was the - M.P. And he was the landlord there. And then after he gave up or he died - but Tynby Hall is - came here ever since. But how many 
years I just can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So who was the landlord before Harry Lawson, would that be Harold Wilson?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. That's when the Buildings were first built.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of landlord was he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well, I - I've got a slight recollection. He was a -
 H.P. I think for this borough. Well I'm not sure. But this, yes. But he was a tall fellow, that's all I can say about him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did he ever do repairs and things like that to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, we - we had to do our own repairs, you see. This building - this 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Building{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was - built first. I think - from number - 19 - College Buildings to 62 - it was made after. And the full - first woman - lived here, in number 70, downstairs, her name is Mrs Banyard, from the hay yard in Whitechapel Grove. And she 
had her family here, I think it was two boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So in 31 College buildings you had two rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was that a kitchen and a bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, a bedroom, but I used to sleep in the kitchen. The rooms only four and six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You didn't have any kind of dining room or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no. No. And our toilet was outside on the landing. But it was - on the level.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were there any gardens or anything like that in these places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So it was more or less a self-contained flat really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 That's it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have any lodgers or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. Well - never had no room for lodgers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your mother work before she got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 She had - yes. She was a cook - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Rushbrook Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, opposite Spitalfields Market. Called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}York{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And the Elmer - was at - mother and son had them two coppershops opposite {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bowsfield Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, the - the Elmer and the York.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Is this your real mother or your step-mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 My step-mother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did she work after she got married to your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
She never went out to work 'til later in years. When things was a bit bad and I suppose she couldn't manage on the money that was given to her, and she went into a sweet factory and a - she was a forelady - in - in Bat - in - in 
Church - no, in Church Lane, you know where the Post Office is? Over here. Well near there. Name of - Austin's, I think his name was Austins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your real mother work before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, she worked in the dairy. So I was told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did she do any work after she married your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. I don't think they was married long enough when she died. 'Cos she was only - thirty-six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What did she die of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - I've never been told by my father. But my friend, Mrs Boughton - she told me - my father told her that she died of the kidneys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I suppose you were too young to remember much about her really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well I don't - not me own mother. But - from what I hear from my father - she was a lovely woman. Golden hair. Hair always loo
ked beautiful. And I'll tell you another thing. When - my - step-mother died - we used to have a neighbour here, she was an old neighbour with Mrs Banyard. She lived here downstairs. And her name was Mrs Earley, and she knew my mother. And she - said what
 a lovely woman she was, she always had fair hair. And always a white starched apron. But that's all I can - I don't even remember her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How did you get on with your step-mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Very nice. Two good mothers I've had. Whatever I wanted - and that -
 I had. But there was two photographs of - of my own mother and my step-mother. I could show - having a joke one day - this neighbour, Mrs Earl, says - look Mr Curle, she said, where do you want to be buried? Is a joke. So he said, well, he said, I love R
ose, that's my own mum. And I love Jane. Well that's where I want to be buried. With Jane. I give him his wish. I've had two good wives. But I wish I had knew more about my own mother than I had. But my step-mother, she was one of the best in this world.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Could you take worries and things like that to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. And I had a jolly jolly good step-mother, she - give me everything I wanted. Very good. That's all I can say about her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How was your father, did you get on all right with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Who, me? Yes. He was a - a - a very pair for - a father and daughter. I loved my father. He never swore, never hit me. That's a lot to say. Isn't it? And whatever I fancied - I fancied you see, money went to it. And my step-mother was one of the -
 most wonderful women - herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
If you did anything wrong what would happen, say you were naughty in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - oh my father never interfered. I might get a smacking off of my step-mother. Put to bed. And that was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What k
ind of things do you think they brought you up to believe were important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - well - my father and also my step-mother - always told me and still with me now - that when you go out - when I was about getting on for fourteen, my step-mother s
ays to me, now you're going out to work. But you're going to mix with different people. Got your eyes to see, your nose breathe - keep your mouth shut.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did that apply when grown ups were talking, what would happen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh there were - there's t
hings - secrets been told to me for - lots and lots of people and there's never a word said about it. And I never repeat. I worked at the baths. Mile End baths, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Golden Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} baths, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Beck Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Ratcliffe baths. Well you see things, well you just keep your
 mouth shut. But I got on very very well with all the people at the baths. And I was a cigarette maker - about twenty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you do cigarette making first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, first. And I went off in - when I lost my mother - step-mother - that - I was ou
t of work for about three months, then I started - at Golden Street baths, 'til - we had - attendants. But it's jolly hard work. But there, in those days, we used to have because - I had my father out of work. And I was out of work. And he only had ten sh
illings a week coming in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When was he out of work from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He worked - at - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}King David Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Shadwell - for a number of years, but they pulled - Shadwell police station down. But he was only - like an errand boy - errand boy for the - policemen, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When did he give up the milk round?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I think it was in 19 - 21.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So he worked quite a lot after that on and off did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
On and off, he - I think he worked at Shadwell for a - about two or three years or more. And I'd been a cigar
ette maker for cigarette - twenty years, and I was working with the baths in 1932 - for about two years, and then we only got ten weeks work in the year. And then afterwards when things were a bit bad - they couldn't get the women to work - bath work, wel
l
 I - or if anybody was sick and ill I used to go and do - the relief for them 'til they come back, because they used to send me a telegram from a Labour Exchange. And they'd be about four or five weeks, mind you, we only got two - ten weeks work in a year
. So we had to manage on that. I've got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So it was quite hard in those years altogether wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh it was, very hard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was it very hard when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. I had a good life. See, my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 trouble}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843  started when my step-mother 
was taken had with cancer. And in 1930. 1927. And she had to attend a hospital. They took her in. They couldn't do no - nothing. Then she laid in bed for a whole year. With cancer. But in all, attending hospital and treatment, she was under the - King Geo
rge V's surgeon, Doctor Suitor, and he said, cannot nothing be done - if - if you can do anything - don't have to cut her open and sew her up again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your mother or step-mother ever help anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. What, me step-mother? N
o, not me mother, me step-mother, no, I used to go to work - at cigarette making, come home and do. Send the sheets out, and I used to - night time used to do the washing. And clear out the place for them if they had no help. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever help while you were a little girl, while you were at school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, I used to - I used to have to do - hearthstone steps, wash them. And I used to go round - the place - if my mother was at work - and that, I used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your father do anything in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. Because his hours was too long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of hours were they then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
He used to - start - if he had a look out cowing - he used to go - leave home at three o'clock. He used to - leave the cow, feed it, and he used to milk it abo
ut five o'clock. A bucket - bucket of water, like ordinary bucket - of - he used, the first the thing you use is - that was milked, but - that milk - was thrown away, the first bucket of the new cow was - thrown away, because - the milk traveling upset th
e
 bag. So therefore always threw them away. But after that, I used to - myself used to have the two glasses of milk straight from the cow. When I used to go to school - I used to go and - my mother used to fetch me round a bottle of hot milk, and a couple 
of cakes. Soon as I come home from school I had one glass of milk, and about seven o'clock I used to have another glass of milk with a cake and to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you go home from school to dinner at lunchtime in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So whe
n would you have the cake and glass of milk in the daytime when your mother brought it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh well, my mum take it to the school in the morning, ten o'clock, you see, and I used to have a cake then. See, I used to come home for me dinner. And when I use
d to - go back to school finish at four o'clock, always had a - a cup of milk, or two and a cake, and - a little bit of tea, like cup of tea or a - slice of bread. I always had hot milk - and a cake before I went to bed. In my younger years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were ther
e lots of these little farms around this area? Was it just cows that your uncle had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Only cowsheds with the cows in. There's one, as I showed you, down there. Well that used to be - what they called the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 tender ground}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 . Well if you walk down - there - right through what they call {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Tilly Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, you go into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bell Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. That's the next turning, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Bell Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and there was a name of Jones' had that place. And they had over thirty cows there. And this Joe, he was a Welshman, and he used to milk all those thirty 
cows. Yes. They had thirty cows in the other sheds. They didn't belong to my uncle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How many cows did your uncle have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
I think it was thirteen or fourteen. You see - the shops here - the cow she'd was here. And the horse, Tommy - stables there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He'd have one horse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 One horse, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What did he store the milk in?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - the milk was in big - big - no turns, but big - pails. But steel. And - the Jewish people also English people used to come round early in the morning, when the milk was hot. And the - hot milk from the cows - but the stere - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 pasteurized}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843  milk was threeha'pence a pint. 'Cos my dad used to go to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Liverpool Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, eight o'clock at night, and collect it from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Chelmsford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. It - the train used to come in about half past eight. Then he used to deliver eight and nine coffee shops, and public houses round here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 They used to sell milk in the pubs did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No - it was just the families who kept the pubs. You see, they might have two pints three pints. But people rou
nd here - the Jewish people, they used to have like hot milk. And the Jewish peoples holiday, what they call the Passover - my uncle - employed - a father and a daughter, because they mustn't - Jewish people has got certain utensils - to use for that spec
ial holiday, Passover. And my - aunt - dad - my uncle had - new shanks made, and the big bowl - big bowl for the people who was what they called from \{ILLEGIBLE\}
, like religious. And he used to serve it with the measures, new measures and the glasses if anybody wanted a glass of hot milk. That was in the Jewish religion. They used to like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 There would be a lot of Jewish people living round here wouldn't there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. Yes. And of course my uncle used to - have cans made only for that holiday,
 for one week. But they was washed, dried out, and put away 'til the following year. Yes, thirteen or fourteen cows my father milked. And the - they used to come up about four o'clock in the morning, if he had a new cow. And he'd chain them up, give them 
some food, then milk the cow, as I said before, used to throw that - big pail of milk, big pail - of milk away. Then about two hours later - used to milk the cows.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
You said you'd come home in the evenings and do the washing when you were at work, was the washing done at home when you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - no, there were sheets sent out when my mother was ill. Of course my mother had to do the - other things - before she was taken ill. Used to have a wash house upstairs. Well when mum - said mum was ill, I'd come home and wash things out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say you had a wash house upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, in - under there. My mother used to go washing - Monday mornings. Get up about six o'clock in the morning, and finish about nine. But when she was taken
 ill, my step-mother, she - I used to come home and do little things. Like washing, when she was very ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
In the days when you went to school or before you went to school would your mother make the family clothes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. My mother made all my clothes. All my underclothes, and my dresses.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
What about your father's clothes, did they buy them, did she make your father's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. She used to buy - used to be a shop down the - bottom here, name of Collins, where the Whitechapel - opp
osite Whitechapel church now. And she used to buy his aprons for the round in the milk - his shirts, his pants - and even his little scarves, to wear while he was working. 'Cos he used to work - long hours. He used to start - about six in the morning, mil
k
 his cows, feed the cows, and - he used to come home to breakfast at half past eight. And - he used to have a wash, have a lay down, get up - go, and - clean the - the cans out, get his churns ready for night time. To take up Liverpool street, to get the 
- urns for milk. He had eight coffee shops to serve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did he deliver to people around the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Not many. Not many. His trade was in Spitalfields Market, pubs and the coffee shops. But he did serve - some private customers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So what time would he be back in the evening, about nine o'clock at night?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. Later. He used to be done about - half past ten. Come home. Have a wash, have his supper, and then he had to do his books, from what he sold - that day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you wouldn't see a lot of him during the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. And he worked right - well he never used to get into bed 'til about twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 And he'd have to be up again by five to get to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So he wouldn't have much time for going out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, only his week's holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 That'd be - about September, used to go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Yarmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And my uncle used to take over the work. But that one week holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did he have any Bank Holidays or anything like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. Seven days a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He worked Sunday as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, oh yes. Never had no holidays at all, only that one week in Yarmouth, September.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did everybody go then, your mother and yourself and him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, oh yes, for a whole week. And we used to go by train from Liverpo
ol Street, and it was called - the Prince's Excursion, to Yarmouth. We used to catch the half past six train and get down there by nine. I think it was only about - ten shillings each. So it only worked out thirty shillings. And you'd got about hundred an
d forty or fifty miles to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever go on any other outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Never. No, he was working wasn't he.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you go anywhere with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
And - no. Oh, well - some - no, when he - packed - when he packed up - there - they used to go to Chelmsford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Is this after the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, after - yes, after the first world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
If your mother wasn't working did she ever take you anywhere on her own, say shopping or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. We used to go shopping together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where would the shops be, round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. The shops were a bit down here. I mean to say we used to go to Bethnal Green. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Watney Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And - get a joint - of lamb - for half a crown. Over at Benny. Woods, the same again, and o
ver Benny Woods it was always - you could get a leg of lamb for half a crown, and pieces on top. You could. But of course I don't suppose you've ever heard of it, aitch bone of beef. Have you? Yes. Now. Aitch bone of beef had a very very big bone in it. A
n
d they used to cut it up - into joints but you couldn't make many - they used to cut it up into joints, but they used to weight about ten to twelve pound - because it's got that big bone in it. But it only cost fourpence ha'penny a pound in those days. My
 
mother used to take that bone out - she'd cut up - a piece for puddings, meat puddings. Next day she'd have friend steak. She did. Meat pies. She used to make. And a roast on a Sunday. And what was left - she used to stew up - and onions, carrots and turn
ips, and used - of course that used to last us 'til about Wednesday. That joint did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What would you have from Wednesday on during the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well we - my mother was a - had a bit of fried fish. 'Course my mother always fried her own fish you see. My father liked a bit of liver. I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would he come home for his evening meal before going out again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He used to have a tea - he used to have a supper when he come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 At half past ten at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Had a supper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When would you eat in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh I - I was eating about - seven o'clock. But she always cooked a meal for my father when he come home at half past ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would you have a cooked meal in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Not now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I mean in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No
. No, my mother used to get me something else. I might have bacon and egg, but that was all. But my mother always cooked a meal for my father when he come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your father come home at midday for a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Two o'clock. Yes, he had his meal, a
 - a good meal there, but then he used to have a lay down to three o'clock. Say from two to four. He takes an hour for his - hour, have a - then he used to get up and wash and get ready and get all the churns - the churns ready, the cows ready, the horses
 ready, before he went up to Liverpool Street - to get that other - pasteurized milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
So practically the only meal you'd have as a family would be the breakfast time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - Sunday - he used to work all day. So he used to work and have his meal just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You'd be home on Saturday and Sunday wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. Not my father, he worked the whole seven days a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 But you'd have your meals with him on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Oh Sundays and that was about all because milking co
ws - you don't know what's coming in as regards of - straw, grains, foodstuffs for the cows, you see, and that's why - the meals was irregular for my father. My mother - and me we used to have our meals at the regular time, if I went to school, my meal wa
s waiting - when I come home from school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What time would you come home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
At about half past four. You see, 'cos I used to come home to dinner at - twelve. Never used to go back to two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would you have a cooked meal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh 
yes. Yes. Yes, from twelve 'til two we used to come home from school, but there was always a cooked meal. I mean there might be - say a kipper if you can afford it. Bit of bread and cheese, cucumber.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of things would you eat for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well - now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 In those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - bananas, bit of fruit and bread and butter. And - I always had my milk as I've told you. And we'd - I might have some porridge. They was very hard times but - a little cost - is a buy - say a box of anything, 
used to last - two or three days. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How often a week would you say you had meat in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well, in those days - well practically about - five - five days a week. But we had fish. Fish, my mum used to fry her own fish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say you had milk with most meals, would you have any other drink at all?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, no, not exactly. I liked me milk - I used to like me milk, hot that was. But - as regards a drink you couldn't have none.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Something like tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh tea, I used to have tea
. And I'm not a lover of coffee or - or cocoa. Only me tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have any tinned meat in those times?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well there was days you had to have. But of course it was cheap, so it was cheaper than the meat. Really - cheapest there was. The meat was
 cheap enough. But sometimes she'd say, oh I can't afford that, I'll have a little bit of tinned salmon 'Cos corned beef in those days was wrapped. Down at - down the bottom here there used to be a shop belonged to Kennedy. They had tripe. Cow hell. Brown
. Liver. And that brown was really lovely, with a few potatoes, little bit of green, that was the meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your mother ever make things like bread or jam or pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Used to make jam, but - no bread. We couldn't do it. In two rooms you only had the one fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of cooker did she cook on, did your mother do all the cooking?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh - she was a lovely cook. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of cooker did she have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
She - cooker? She only had the fire. To cook by. And the - saucepans used to be 
on the hob. Yes. You see, my mother used to - say she got a joint. Say a leg of lamb or anything for Sunday joint, there'd be three saucepans on the hob, which would be one for greens, one for the potatoes. She used to bake those potatoes in the oven, wit
h the joint.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you did have an oven arrangement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. Yes. See. Here, there was oven there. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So it was like a fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 It's a fire, got to use fuel. Coal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 But it's a stove as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. All black. It's all black. An
d the coal in those days - was - years and years ago was only - one and six a hundredweight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
This was an actual stove in the room, it wasn't just a fireplace with a hearth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 It was just a fireplace with a hearth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How could you cook a roast joint on a fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well you had the oven - beside of the fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 There was actually a container you could put it in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
See the centre used to be a fire such as this you see, here's the fire, here is a plate on top for the soot to go through, and my mother used to put three saucepans on for the vegetables. And this through here. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say she made her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would she ever make things like medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would she or your father ever brew any beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. Never brewed nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you used to eat in the kitchen as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes. There was only the kitchen. And my bed was in the kitchen at the time. She made plenty of pastry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You said she was a cook before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brushfield Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, in a coffee shop. And big mug of tea for a penny. A teacake used to be toasted. Tuppence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have any extra food or anything at Christmas time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well - we used to have a fowl. And if my mother could afford a bit of }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 pork}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
 we used to have that, and the Christmas pudding - and a custard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would you have anybody round at Christmastime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. Very seldom 'cos my father had to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 On Christmas Day as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, yes. He worked the whole seven
 days a week. All the year round 'til he got his week's holiday. That was - four o'clock - in the morning he used to get up and go right round - well he never had far to go. And he used to come home he used to have a rest during the day. Say for about an 
hour and a half.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So your mother and father really wouldn't go out very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. Not often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
You say you used to go shopping with your mother, would you go anywhere else with your mother, would she take you anywhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well we used
 to go see - I had a - she had sisters. We used to go down and see them in Plaistow. In Plaistow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where's that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
A number five bus from here now - takes you right to Plaistow. But - I used to stay with my - mother's mother - at Plaistow in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Croydon Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - for about a month. But - I see all the relatives of her sisters and brothers then. But my mother couldn't do - on account of my father working.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
What time of year would that be when you went there for a month, in the summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. In the summertime. Of what year? Now let me see. About 1910.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You just went for that one year, that one month?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You didn't go every year for a month?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no. No, she used to go there, well it only takes about half hour to get there. And I 
used to be like being down then to the garden. And I was about eight years old when I used to go down there, and my mother used to come down, and - see me about once a week, see how I was getting - and then I - my mother had a cousin over 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Greenwich{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I used to stay there longer. As a child. When I was about seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did they ever come up to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, they did, from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Greenwich{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Now and again. Of course Mr Gordon works at the gas company in - in Greenwich.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Can you ever remember at mealtimes whethe
r your mother ever had less so that your father or yourself could have more food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
If I - my? Oh yes, there was a little bit more left - at the meal, but not much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Do you remember your mother deliberately having less so there'd be more to go round?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Less? Oh yes, might be enough if company come home - half past ten - to have that before he went to bed. Because he had his meal midday - two o'clock. But he wouldn't get nothing more - 'til about eleven at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you told to eat the me
al in a certain way, to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. Yes. Right way to - serve and never talk while you're eating.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Who told you that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 My mother. And say grace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you allowed to bring books or toys to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh I could - could - have read, and I've had - toys, as a youngster. Been presents to me - from Greenwich. I had a big doll once. And they bought that for me. And - other little things - what my mother's mother give me. She give me little chain - b
ut it was gold in those days. But I lost it. And my mother was very annoyed. So I never got nothing else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have anything special in birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, I wouldn't have nobody in here - no neighbours, might have - might have a couple of - little girls in. Straight from school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were there any neighbours children in College Buildings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, never used to have 'em. No. No. I might fetch a couple from school who I used to like - and play with. But that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where would you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 In the yard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Outside the back here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of things would you play there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - we used to play - throwing the ball with the - back, and - what other games used to have? Tennis sometimes. We used to put a - a - a block across the yard here, and a bit of string and knock it over. And in \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 Hall - I was only a - child, I used to go to Swedish Drill. Swedish Drill. In \{ILLEGIBLE\} Hall.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What's that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Jump over the horse. Yes. I enjoyed that very much. Well
, it - set your muscles a going. It was a very nice - lesson they had there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you allowed to play in the street at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. We used to have - as I told you before - a man come round with an organ name of Percy. And I'd go there - oh, lik
e to show off, being children - we used to just dance around, and then he'd say, go on, there's some to go up. He was a very nice - he was old - but very nice. But so that's the only games - I used to go to the club, St Judes, next to \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 Hall. As I grow - grow older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What was that, a youth club kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes. Well it was about twelves and thirteens it was. And Miss Mary Hughes - she used to run the dialogues for shows to get the money for the church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of shows would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Ordinary - like - myself. About elevens and twelves. And the mothers and fathers come see us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you write them yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No, she wrote them, but she used to get them other dialogues, and - we used to practice what she wanted us to do. And our parents come with us, you see - three - pence to go in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was there much organised by \{ILLEGIBLE\} Hall apart from that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. I mean to say, in the church next door there was plenty going - plenty - of clubs going there, even 
for boys - and for girls. And then we used to have a mixed - and we used to have a party, Miss Mary Hughes - and - Reverend Carter and his wife used to come and give us to the teas. Or give out the teas to the mothers and fathers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How often a week would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - that - used to be now and again, only now and again. You see. Reverend Carter - he liked putting up - the dialogues going to be Miss Mary Hughes - we used to go round there and we used to have fun. Practice. And practice for the dial
ogue, and then on the Saturday - the mothers and fathers used to come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So there were all sorts of things going on really just in that area?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, in the circle. Yes. I mean to say, belonging to a church - and the people - and neighbours here was
 very friendly. How that Mrs Banyard, from the hay yard from Whitechapel was the first in here, at number 70, she - she used to go - belong to the church, and she used to make cakes - if there was a party going on. And - Mrs Carter, she used to do things 
- but Miss Hughes used to do the organising of everything. It was a pity they went down with the Titanic, it was a terrible thing. 'Cos she was a very very nice man. Reverend Carter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 They were on the Titanic were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Travelling to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} 
and the iceberg - cut them in half. They could have saved Mrs Carter. She said, where my husband goes I go. So it was left at that and she went down. And Miss Mary Hughes, Mrs Carter's sister. She had a place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Eurns Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. For girls. And - she - really - 
she was properly upset when the sister - went with her husband. But the church carried on for a bit longer, and then Mr and Mrs Parker came - to run the church. They run it for a number of years, Mrs and Mr Carter, they even had a servant. Right next to 
\{ILLEGIBLE\} Hall. But he was a lovely man. No children they never had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was it a Church of England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. Same as Springfields.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you go to this every Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Sunday. I used to go three times a day. I used to go when I was young
, St Jueds. But when I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 started}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
 school, my mother says to me, well - as you're going to the school you'd better go to the same - morning service, Sunday school and your evening service there. Which I did do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your mother go to church as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Your father would be working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Working. That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do you remember being a member of the church choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. Remember that. And that Mrs Banyard's sons - used to be - in the choir there. 'Course and now - today there's women aren't there in churches - in the choir - Springfields.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 But there weren't in those days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Not - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were they all male choirs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
All male choirs. But now they have women. 'Cos I've been to church the other week, but - of course - that's been done up, Spitalfields, and there was only about five in the choir. There used to be about fifteen. But all neighbours. All neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your mother or father or yourself ever play a musical instrument or sing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. My father 
was a busy man - when he was single. Because - he had to read to his father, my grandfather, which was a lovely man too. He always read a book to him - night time, before he ever got married to my own mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you see much of your grandfather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes. Yes. I had to go to me grandfather - every Sunday morning before I went to church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where did he live, just round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Did you know Stepney Green Station? Stepney Green station. He lived right opposite. I used to always lookout the window
 at ten o'clock, about half past nine, see if I was coming along. And - he had the Bible there on the table and I had to read a verse to him. He said, well now you've got a good home, go to church. I said, yes granddad. And he always left a little bag of 
sweets and a threepenny bit. And there was horse busses in those days, from Stepney Green - not station - Jstepney Green right past here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say your father used to read to your grandfather before he married?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your father ever read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. Never read to me at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your mother ever read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well she used to tread books. Like, but - that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of books were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh well, I really can't - re - remember. But my father always said
 - that he read to my grandfather a book a night. A night. When he was single. And - he used to tell him about - he said it used to take him about three hours. But he always went to bed eleven o'clock. But my grandfather was a very intelligent man, so was
 my father. They spoke about different things - of their younger years. What happened to 'em. And my grandfather, he used to - check on my father, being the eldest of the family - to look after the other sisters and brothers. But very nice man.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were there many books and magazines in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. Oh yes. My father - when he was - got married to my own mother - he told me he used to have books - and read them. Encyclopaedias, and he - politics. He was very - up with that really in politics. A
nd anything was going on in the world, and he could talk about the different countries, my father, though he never went away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He never went abroad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. By he used to go to the library and buy books, my father. Just after be got married to my own mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say he was interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes, he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 In what was was he interested in politics, did he go to any meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
He used to go to couple of meetings 'cos it - in those days - the meetings was only Liberals and
 Conservatives. But he used to like to - go and hear what they'd say, and any questions - he used to ask, and that's how he come - very interested in politics really. 'Cos -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did he ever talk about politics when he was at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well he did, yes. 
Well I mean to say in those days my dear he - he used to talk about the Liberals and Conservatives, the different countries of the world, of what he's road, my father. But of course today - there's all dominations of people, and also different - people do
ing different things isn't there. You see? Years ago it was only Liberals and Conservatives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What did he vote, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 My father was a Liberal. Always -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did he ever do anything at election time, help the party organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, no. No, well he was working wasn't he, on a milk round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Sometimes the employees had to vote the way the employer wanted them to vote didn't they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do you think that was true in your father's case?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 But the interest of my father, he 
only went - but - he - he was interested in books to read - about the politics, and he just kept himself - his views what he thought was right, and he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He didn't try to push them on to other people at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh no, he'd never do that. Well I mean
 to say, everybody to their own views. I mean to say there's today there's Communists, Liberals, Conservatives. There might be some others - different voting people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was your mother interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 Well I - I - that I can\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843  say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was your step-mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - yes, whatever my father done my mother always followed suit. I mean to say, she'll have her say the same as me father would. I mean to say he might get into company with working with. No, Liberals this, Conservatives that. Whi
ch is true, isn't it? So therefore he should be - had to shut up then. 'Cos it leads to arguments, and being nasty. I mean to say of today - they don't know what to vote for. Do they? They say, oh I'll vote Conservatives. Well it's a terrible thing. I mea
n
 to say, the way the country is off today - it - nobody seems to know where they are really. Of course, if you vote for Conservatives, Liberal, or - like they do now, Communist - they do always - demanding, like the railways. Get the union men out. Now my
 
father never believed in unions. Never believed in unions. But now they want to get all the unions out don't they, the men. Go to the union. But where do we get them all? They want the money, extra money of today don't they. They went pounds. You - miners
,
 they deserve every penny they get. But when a person works in a factory - we want another five pound rise, we - they want twenty pound a week money, forty pound. Look at the dockers. I think it's did graceful. Oh I'd give everybody a fair wage. We know t
h
ings are different to my time. The money's about. But how do they spend it? Well I tell you. I was out yesterday, the little kids - they wanted this, they wanted that. One had - one balloon - one of them things that goes round - he wanted bag of sweets. A
nd he wanted a little tiny boat. Well that's all money. And you can't - cannot do all that on that one person's money if the wife - doesn't go out to work. Can you? But all women of today do work. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Didn't they in your time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh no. My father 
- well my father used to work all day and my mother had to be here to - wait on him. I mean to say, they was hours - about fourteen or fifteen hours a day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would she ever go out on her own anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. But she used to - leave - his meals
 - on the table - but if he was sitting to have a rest, he used to hot it up. But it was very seldom. They both cared for one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where would she go if she did go out on her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh she went to - relatives, like to her mother. To her mother
 and father in Plaistow. She never went - always knew where we mother went. 'Cos -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did she have any special friends around here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. Only my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What about your father, did he have any special friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. Nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So they just had each other more or less?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I mean to say, he couldn't go out. All - all them hours a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
When you were at school still did you ever go to places like theatres or cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, we never went - in those days. They do now. I mean to 
say they can go to - as I say - whichever art gallery, and they can see something - for what they can learn. We never had that. We had to go to school, do our lessons. Empire Day. We went to church. And on the - on the same sect as Boothills church we use
d to have our little flags, what is the meaning of Empire Day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Is that May the twenty-fourth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
That's right. And we should - after the church service we had to come home. But we never had no outings. Only once. I can ever remember going out - and 
I thought to myself, well, I'm - I'm very lucky girl. And we all went to Chingford. To Mr Figgs. That was his name. And - Mr Figgs we tricked. And we used to have a tea there. Give us a - bun, bread and butter, jam - and - we used }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 to try}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843  and get a present for mother, to fetch home, we'd been to Chingford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would this be with the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. The school days. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What time of year was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well I started at Spitalfields - Spitalfields - in 1906. I was - we should go - go there, but I
 was there - St Judes - and St Judes, Colonel Barnet. I think - no, it wasn't called - it was called Commercial Street, but - I was there for about couple of years, then me mother says to me, well - as you're going to Christchurch - better go to church th
ere. So I went there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was that a church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, oh yes. There. I - I was at - went there about couple of weeks back to the church, but the church - is got to be done up, through the bombing, it's old. So they've got the - place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hambury Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Where we - as youngsters, used to have plants sent to us, geraniums - and fuschias. And we used to have to grow 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you had your own allotment really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, we used to fetch 'em home. And my father and mother used to - try and get them on. And I - I won the first prize once, I can just about remember that. But they was happy days down Christchurch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So was this the church next door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. That's St Judes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Then you moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Christchurch{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, and went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Christchurch{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} up here. Yes. Yes, mother said it'd be better for me. Because - I - I like - both of the vicars and that, but my mother used to go shopping up that way, in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brick Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Which one was the church that the Carters ran?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 St Judes. One next door - 
to Tonby Hall. Then they knocked it down, because - there was their vicarage where they lived. And in - in between - the passage in the - open, there was a little fountain that anybody can go and have a drink of water - with Christ - in the centre. Real b
eautiful it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 That's been knocked down you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh it's all knocked down now. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever go on any church outings at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, I've only been to one, that was Little Hampton about four year ago from Christchurch.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You didn't go to any when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were there any Sunday school outings then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, there wasn't any in those days. Well really I mean to say the church is supported - the Roman Catholics are not, are they? You see. So - what money w
e had - for the church - it always got rebuilt in some way or other. But of course that's not been open for years now, it's rebuilt. You see, it's old, you see, but - they're going to do it up, they've done the bells. The ten bells or something - they've 
got them fixed up about six months ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Is Spitalfields a Roman Catholic one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, not Spitalfields. No, Church of England. 'Cos the schools the back of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you went to two schools in all, you went to St Judes and Christchurch?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Chris
tchurch and St Judes. Well that was Commercial Street. Next to the church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was that a church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 St Judes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How did you like school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh I enjoyed it very much for the - there. As regards learning me lessons as 
far as I can learn. But - me dad - says to me, what would you like to go to? So I said, well - I don't know dad. So my mother says, well - let her have her pick. And I fancied - the tobacco trade. So - a woman was living in College Buildings there, she to
ok me. And that was - that was in 1912. And I was a - had to do all the odd jobs. Half a crown a week. But when I learnt - cigarette making - I got a rise of a half a crown. And then I come a full blown - cigarette maker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have to go through any kind of apprenticeship for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So what kind of hours did you start off at?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 A day was from eight to half past six.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would you have a break in the middle of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, our midday - from twelve 'til one. And four o'clock 
we used to have a cup of tea. That was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How much would you get for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Half a crown.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was that seven days a week or six?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, no, that was six days a week. Five - five and a half days a week. Yes. Five and a half days a week for half a crown a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What did you have to do in the first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well I had to - wait on the cigarette makers. Give - get their tobacco. The cases, you know the cases. Had to get them for them. And then I learned cutting - the cigarettes. I did, an
d - after that they said well it's about time - that you tried to - make cigarettes, so I started to learn. Well that took me - not long to learn because - I used to, before the forelady came in, I used to go on that vat, practice. And when I saw her I us
e
d to jump off - and I'd made about twenty. And that's how you got to learn. But you had to buy your own utensils. Yes. And it's what they call a clonky, you know butter paper? What they wrap the butter in. Well it's was thicker than that, it's thick, and 
y
ou roll the cigarettes with that. But you come to a point - and - and a knitting needle you cut down the size, because all sizes cigarettes. And we used to push 'em up through that and cut them. 'Course the cigarette scissors was round. To take it - to th
e edge of the case.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What would you used the butter paper for? Not for the actual wrapper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, it - it's like that - as I tried to explain to you, but it's very stiff paper. And - we had to cut that - to a point that you can get the paper on - as 
you rolled it, with the clonky. What they call a clonky. And that's only a bit of - ledger paper. Which was thick. You see, and this clonky - that was a clonky and a paper - the butter paper was thick, and used to roll the tobacco. But you've got to make 
d
ifferent size cigarettes. And then you had to try 'em out. But the men - we used to do that sometimes, a certain heat. You see, but now they make 'em by machine. But I used to catch the cigarettes - on the machine. Used to go at thousand a minute - on the
 machine. I used to make about two thousand a day. Two to three thousand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 And they were all kinds were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes, and different sizes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would they be different brand names?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have to put them into boxes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 That's
 right. Yes. And there used to be some made for - weight, to be weighed. Pound boxes, half a pound. Perhaps you've heard the - Beulays - cigarettes. Well, Dunhills. We used to make them years and years ago. Yes, so of course I've - I've enjoyed me work. A
n
d - my friend, she used to start making cigarettes. And - she said, well - cut me some clonkies, and - you go on my - my treadle when Goldie's not here, that was the forelady, and - I used to - go on and try me hand at cigarette making there. And that's w
here I knew me friend from. Fifty-eight years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You did that 'til about 1930 when your step-mother died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, earlier than that. Earlier.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You finished then though did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 1930, yes. We all got the sack. Yes, we all got the sack.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Because of the depression?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. 1930, but I was working at the Ardath. In 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Worship Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Near Aldgate. Yes, about fourteen hundred makers got the sack. Then 1932, I started down the baths. But in the meantime, I had my father out of work. I was out of
 work. I run that house for the dole, and I never had nothing coming in. So only had ten shillings a week to keep my father and me on. Rent was only four and six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So it hadn't gone up since when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you get on all right with the employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, very nice indeed. And always got a Christmas box from 'em. Always got five shillings, which was a lot in those days. You see? For the cigarette making. We always got - sometimes - we got cigarettes if you wanted - wel
l I never smoked then. Then they used to buy us a box chocolates. At the Radath in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Worship Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 everybody had a box of chocolates Christmas. But you could buy cigarettes there. Two shillings for twenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you meet any new friends at this time when you first started working?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. I've only had one friend. That was in 1912, at the B.D.P.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What's the B.D.D.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Down here was - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Commercial Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, but it's not there now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What does it stand for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh I don't know what it stan
ds for. B.D.V. I do know it, but I can't remember it now. B.D.V. See there was only - there was a family of them name of Philips. Godfrey Philips was the name of the people who run it. There was the father, Gerald, Spencer - I worked with the old people. 
But I've heard say - that one of the sons has died, and only a few weeks back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was it a tobacco place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, down Commercial Street. B.D.V., that's where I first started. And 1912 - and - my friend came in 1914. And - we all got the sack from ther
e, 'course - it was very bad the trade were - was, so - we started at the Ardath. I was there about fifteen years. And we all got the sack. In 1930, in 1932 - I started down the baths.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you get more money when you went to the Ardath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well, th
e things rose in the thousand. You see. At the B.D.V. we used to get I think about two and six a thousand. But as time went on at the Ardath we used to get four and six a thousand. We did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How long would it take you to do a thousand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh a thousa
nd, you'd do - a thousand in a morning, from eight o'clock - 'to - - one. And then we used to work 'til half past six, sometimes I'd make about eleven or twelve hundred in the afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever do any training for this, apart from on the spot, y
ou didn't go to any evening classes or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, oh no, no. You see, you learnt - years ago - as - if you went into a factory and you give your mind to - to do a job - you say, well - come on, we're learning you. Or you watch and you'll
 see. You see, and then - as it got on in years - we used to teach others you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you enjoy this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. Cigarettes. 'Cos used to gold tip and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 They used to have tips in those days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Gold tip. There is - have cigare
tte - at the Ardath, ladies cigarettes. A very very small cigarette. There was. Twenty-two carat gold. Yes. The tips were. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When you left school did you feel that school was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 good}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843  experience, that you'd got something out of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well - we ne
ver got - anything out of it, there was your lessons about - geography, your sums - religion, and we who leave - we come to a point - you've got think things out for yourself. About what - you'd like to be at, or what you learn from school days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your teachers ever ask you what you'd like to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no. No. But I've still got me character from 1912, from school. I was a very very good girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you get on O.K. with the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, very well. Very well considering. But I was ill on
ce. And my teacher hit me. Her name - is - was Mrs Crouch, her name was, and she hit me. And there was a lady in the passage over there, in that building, name of - Percy, she come home and said to my step-mother, Mrs Crouch has given your Bella - a smack
 round the face and she's got the \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 of her - marks on her face. So my mother, said, very well, she says, I'll go up to the school. So my mother went saw Mrs Crouch. And my mother told her - to leave me alone, and if she kept on hitting me - she'll
 take me away. And then the schoolmaster, Mister Skinner, he says, look Mrs Curle - she's a good girl. And Mrs Crouch must have lost her temper, so she said, it's not your child. And my mother - was angry. And she turned my face and I'd got the \{
ILLEGIBLE\}
, marks on my face. So what happened. She put me in front of the fire to be a good girl. As I - she done that to me. So my mother soon told her not to put me in front of the fire. Put me at the back. And she said I was naughty. So my mum says, she wasn't 
n
aughty to her father and she wouldn't be naughty to you or to me either. Because I'm fetching me - my child up - to know her manners. But after that she was very nice to me - in my schooldays. So I've had some happy schooldays. And Mister Skinner, when I 
heard about him dying - I went to the memorial service at Spitalfields. I was working in the baths then. Mile End baths. That was very nice at that school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
You say you did sums and geography and scripture and things like that, did they try teach you certain things like punctuality or tidiness or manners,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes, you had to be - you had to be. My mother used to make my clothes. And I always had a clean apron on every morning. As a matter of fact, Mr Skinner and Mrs Skinner - they used to come round
 in the lines - and we used to have prayers and to look to see if everything - was just so in case anybody come. But the vicar - Reverend Chard, of Spitalfields church, always took the morning service. In school. He did. But oh yes - manners, and on my - 
character said - well - well behaved - girl, and very good manners. I've still got it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say you got punished that time, were the teachers very strict as such?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes, very strict. Everything had to be just so. As regards your books, you - had
 homework to do, books for the teachers was put out, monitors we had, I used to do the monitoring sometimes, I used to put the teachers - rules out. Books. And what was on for the day for the teaching. And girls used to follow on. You see, we used to take
 it in turns. And Mr Skinner and Mrs Skinner - often used to come - while the classes was on, the headmaster - to whatever you was learning, he used to - take over from the teacher sometimes, to see that everything was correct.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say your mother went
 round to school that once, did they ever go around to see the teachers on any other occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh no. No. No, they never went round there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did they show much interest in your schoolwork, your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes, they - as a matter fact we - 
my parents used to see 'em in the street and talk to - Mr and Mrs Skinner and they used to tell mum I was getting on all right. With me lessons, and well behaved. So my mother said, yes, that's what I've taught her. And we never answer back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What was the rule when grown ups were speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh you couldn't say nothing. You'd just got to put your hands behind your back - and just turn your head to whatever they were saying because it - it's very rude to listen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Can you remember what your mother
 or your father would say when another child hit you, did that ever happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. That I can't remember, but I - my father - he was - a man like that, to read a book like that. But - I was only young. You see, my father was a great reader. But he'd - t
hey both taught me - to behave myself and always be polite to people. Which I was. So I've got nothing to regret and - about being naughty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
So you can't remember any particular instance when you were naughty and were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes I can. Yes.
 I was sitting round the fire. And - all of a sudden - I wasn't very fond of butter. Butter. Which my mother used to - beat up - Sunday - about ten pints of cream. And I scrapped the butter off - the bread which my mother done which was rather thick and I
 
put it in a piece of paper. And I didn't know what to do with it, but I must have thrown it in the fender, in those days, and it was burning. And my mother says, something's burning. Oh, she says, what have you done? Well I wouldn't tell her untruth. I sa
id, I don't like the thick butter mummy - mother, I says, but I scrapped it off and put it down there because you come in this room. And I was put to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 If you were naughty you were put to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would you say that you receiv
ed your ideas on how to behave yourself from both parents or did your mother or your father play a more important part?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. I was told to - behave - and - if - strangers and my parents both the same. I never sauced them. As - as a youngster I suppose we all get a bit naughty. But - I got punished for it, put to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How old were you when you first went to St Judes school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 St Judes? Oh I think I was about - four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you ever given any lessons at home before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Only manners. Manners. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would took you to school when you first went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 My mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How old were you when you first went there on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well about six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you go all the day when you first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 All day. All day. Yes. All day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What time did school start?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, that's right. Nine o'clock in the morning. Yes, nine o'clock in the morning 'til half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 And you'd come home for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Half past four it finished.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You came home for your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. From twelve 'til one. And they had a soup kitchen. At Spitalfields.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What was that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
For the poor - poor people - poor girls and boys whose mothers couldn't afford to give 'em - a slice of bread. And - this is 
where I'm going to be naughty. I said, to the master, Mister Skinner, Mr Skinner please let me have a ticket for the soup kitchen. So he looked at me and he says, not you Bella? He said, Bella - so he said, well you never had one. And - \{BLANK\}
 Yes, about 
the - soup kitchen. So I said, Mr Skinner, let me have a ticket - for the soup kitchen please. So he looked at me. So he said, why, he said - you want soup today? So he says, well, he says, you're - you've never had one have you? So I said, no, but I want
 to try it. So I give him me farthing. So I went to the soup kitchen, and we had a basin of soup and a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 slice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843  of bread. My mother's waiting for me to come home to have my dinner. And - then - I did - get a good hiding. My mother says to me, where you been? I
 says, I've been to the soup kitchen, Mr - Skinner give me a ticket for a farthing so I've been. I said, and it was very nice. So I got a bit of a good hiding, never went to school. And my mother went up to the - Mr Skinner, the headmaster, and told him n
ever serve me with a soup - ticket for a farthing as she always cooked every day, for the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Why do you think she was annoyed, because you didn't turn up at home and she was worried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I never turned up. And the meal was ready. You see. But I 
thought I was going to be brave and I suppose - a farthing soup - ticket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your mother not like you going to the soup kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. It was only bread and cheese - for lunch - come home to and say a hot - say - egg and bacon or something like that for tea. But when she heard I went to the soup kitchen, I was a real naughty girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Who went to this soup kitchen, was it just people from your own school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. Yes, from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Christchurch{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 They didn't come from all around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, no, no. No, only the school. And that's in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brick Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now. Do you know {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hambury Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}? Well it's just before you come to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hambury Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, on the right as you go from here. You see {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Christchurch{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} up. But I got a good hiding for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Why did these chi
ldren go to the soup kitchen, weren't their mothers home during the day?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well if they went to the soup - kitchen, they had their hour there or two hours there you see, and they never went home, because their mothers never had the money to give them to get them food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was there many children like that at Christchurch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh plenty. Oh yes, plenty in those days. I had - well what my mother could afford. I always had - I mean to say work for the men those days was terrific. They was all out of work. I mean to say there wasn't no dole then. Wasn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Did you ever feel that when you were very young that your mother and father had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes, they had a struggle. I mean to say if we had a - somethings - if it's only
 pieces of stuff - you knew you had the nutriment in it - when you had it at home. You had your hard times. I mean to say - if a man earned twenty-five shillings a week it was a lot. When it wasn't much. But you'd still got to eat. If it's only vegetables
. We all had a very hard time, but my hardest time was - not so bad and I was little as when I lost me step-mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did the other children at school come from similar homes to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 The children? They come from round this neighbourhood. Nowhere else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was it a girls school or a mixed school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Mixed. Boys and girls. But they was all - Jewish and all. You see - when we used to have prayers in the morning - one side of the school in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brick Lane{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} - used to be a class there for only Jewish b
oys and girls, and the Rabbi used to come and take their service. We had folding doors all - four times longer than this, and Mr Chard, our vicar, or Mr Skinner, used to take the lessons for us. But the Jewish boys and girls, they was made separate. The R
abbi to take their - service in the morning. You always had that - just after nine of a morning, to ten o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 The market wouldn't be open on the Sabbath would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. Yes. In those days the market used to open at three o'clock in the morning. Spitalfields Market.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What about the Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
The Lane, they used to open about - seven, or eight. Every day, but they don't do it now. They don't open now 'til about ten - or eleven. You - if you was really wanting something - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 desperate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 , say a 
bit of butter or bred - you could go down the Lane about - half past six or seven, you can get it. You can get it now but some bakers are open. Some of the shops are open to get your butter. If you run short. You see, in those days - they used to open ver
y early. But not now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 They used to be open very late as well didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes. Yes. Well I mean to say my mother used to go out shopping - say Saturday - she used to go sometimes in the morning or in the afternoon. The shops would be open 'til n
ine or ten - o'clock at night. In Aldgate you could get a joint at nine o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would she do quite a bit of her shopping at the Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Not always. No. She used to go around. You see, in Aldgate - down Commercial Street here - apart from the stalls - you go as far as the Minories - know that? You do? Well, from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
Street}}Mansell Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - to - Aldgate - Aldgate station - beyond that all meat shops. Only meat shops alone years ago. And if you go up there about nine o'clock, you get a very cheap joint
. About two shillings, half a crown. Then they'd sell packets. Saveloys, pease pudding. So really at half past ten they was just about closing it up in Aldgate. Same as {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Watney Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. They used to be open 'til late. Brick Lane used to be open 'til late. You see, late at night. But now they're in before five. See, the Lane now shuts up at three o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You were telling me the other day about some organ grinder?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh organ grinder, oh well, he - I don't know whether he lived round here but he was always round here. He used to come round, he had very thick glasses, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 P}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
ercy his name was. Percy. And he used to come - just over there, with his old - all the old fashioned songs, and there used to be the boys and girls from here, over there, we used to dance
 round holding hands. And, you know, give a copper, give him a ha'penny or a penny, you see, about tuppence he - he can get - or threepence he can get a bit of a meal. And that's how he got his living. All the way round. He'd go from here, he'd go round t
he corner, go down the Lane. He would. But he was a nice old man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you used to play in other childrens houses in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, we used to go out - we used to go - what game was it now - we used to touch a lamp post. There used to be from th
is building only. And we used to - go round to the church, come out of church, walk round Aldgate, and - buy some chips. Haporth of chips and a pickled cucumber, and biles. What they call bagles. Bagles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What are they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 They're little round thing
s with a hole in the bread. It'd be about four a penny. There might be about eight of us. And I - go on Bella, you go and get the chips. I used to go and get a pennorth of chips, might have about four or five each. Piece of Bagle, bit of cucumber, the lot
 cost tuppence. Happy days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Would you ever be warned off playing with certain children? Were you ever told not to play with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, not exactly. No. Because really in this building I only played with the children in this building, 
and you know what they were. You see, never no strangers. 'Cos there was a lot of children here. And you knew their families. So therefore - you know who you was playing with. See, but - there might be one or - twice a week they play. 'Cos in the winterti
me you couldn't very well go out. 'Cos weather was too bad in those days. Used to have snow like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What would you play when you were indoors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - I had me homework to do. From school. But - I sometimes my dad learned me to play - cards. Cribbage. And up to this very day I can just play cribbage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your father play cribbage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did they play any games with you, your father and mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. No, well father was at work all day, as you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would other children come in to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What did your mother and father think of you playing games on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well I never had time to play games did I, I used to go to church. See me grandfather. Have me dinner, go to Sunday school, and go to evening service. But not on Sundays - couldn't play with children on Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever go for walks when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well I had - I used to go for walks - I used to walk from here to - Hyde Park. When I first started work. But - as I've said, I used to go there and then - Sundays I had to go and visit me grandfather and grandmother. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You used to go visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I thought you said fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh no, not fishing, no. But - I never used to go for long walks. Though
 IU used to like walking. In Cheapside there used to be some bells ring. And they still ring. 'Cos I've been in the bus and heard them. And I used to love to stand there, listen to the bells.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever go round the City very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, well - the only time I go is when I go to see me friend. You see -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Is this after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, that's after I left school. Yes, I went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where did she live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 She was in Victoria. We've been friends fifty-eight years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You met her at the tobacco place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
That's right, 1914. And she's been a dear friend to me. In sorrows and in joys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You still see her now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Saw her yesterday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever have any hobbies when you were at school still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. We never had t
hat, it was all like teaching to - geography and - about the world a bit. And I used to come home and say to my father - so and so about the world, and - 'course he - he done so much reading, that he can just hit on what I've asked, he can answer me. He c
ould. I used to like doing a little bit of housework and - do vegetables. Anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have anything you had to do regularly as your job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever have any part time jobs or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. No. I - my fathe
r used to clean the shoes and boots. Every other night. My dad. And my mother used to do her washing Mondays, and - all the sewing, what had to be done, she made all my clothes. While I was young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did she make her own clothes as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. Make her own blouses, she used to make her own skirts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What about things like shoes or boots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - well - they kept me all right in shoes and boots, though they were - they wasn't dear but you never had the money to buy 'em so you had to make '
em last. Well shoes now I suppose I'm really careful on now, 'cos they last me four or five years. You see. My mother used to buy them in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brick Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, name of Filomy. And - that name's still there now. And I think my mother used to give about - five or six 
shillings a pair then. 'Course that was a lot of money. It was. But - anyhow - they were things my mother had to go out to work - to make ends meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Before - before she was ever taken ill, she was taken ill in - 1927. That was about 1924.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What did she do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well she was - before she married my father she was a cook. But - she worked in a sweet factory, she was a forelady. Hame of Os - Oswald, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Church Lane{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, past the Post Office there. But she never earned - worked there long because she was taken bad. On and off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How often a week would you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well every day. You've got to have clean clothes on to go to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you changed each day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, I mean to say - mothers of - years 
ago, they used to get pieces of stuff - and make stuff up. Underwear, my mother always made me frocks. And me little knickers and that. All me underwear she used to make.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When would you have baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 A bath? I used to go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Goldsworth Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} baths. Where I used to work -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You didn't have one in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No, nothing like that. No. If I wasn't well my mother used to say - I'll wash your back. And she'd wash me down. Nothing like that then, nothing. I mean to say, years ago there use
d to be - toilets out at - right - out in the open in the yard, years ago. But ours was on the landing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You had a washer upstairs as well didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you had things available?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What time did you have to go to bed when you were very young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh when I was young, six o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you put yourself to bed in those days or did your mother put you to bed?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. Yes. I had to go to bed early. And as I grew older - about seven - in the summertim
e it was about seven or half past seven. Had to go to bed. Winter - time used to be earlier because you couldn't sit up - and burn the fire. My mother and father used to go to bed early. Though it was only one and six a hundredweight but you never had the
 money to spend out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Your mother was in the house quite a lot on her own wasn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
She was. Oh yes. Yes. But - while she had the fire going - she used to make a lot of pastry. That eked out. I mean to say, apart from your food - you had your go
od meals what - substantial meals, but - not a filling meal, so you're full up. The time have those - fried steak and chips and onions can you. Not now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you allowed to choose what you wanted to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What about stuff left uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
About what? Oh I couldn't - must eat what was on the plate. No, and wasn't allowed to do that. And I had to eat every bit up. But my mother knew my appetite, and she knew what to give me. But if I wasn't well I'd say - mummy, I'm 
not well. Then she used to give me according. There's nothing wasted. Nothing wasted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did she serve the food up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 From the stove?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh, from the stove. Yes. Well they had tureens - in those days. Tureens. They're like a - a 
bowl - they've got - it'll hold - they - they are - for vegetables. Tureens they call them. And you - you put your potatoes in one lot, your greens. And also - if you've got other things besides - say you've got a tin of peas, you put them in there. And y
ou serve from the tureens. And my mother used to cut the meat up. And she'd serve from the tureens. China. All china.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have any tinned vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - not exactly because - there was really - you can get them very cheap, I mean to sky,
 you come take potatoes - potatoes. White potatoes, what they call whites now. They're only two - two pound a penny. The - the others - was four pound three - pence. Well you can get a cauliflower, you can get cabbage - for about tuppence. And I - they la
s
t you a - a - day. You serve you round you see. So if you spent tuppence or threepence on the cabbage a day - for a family - there was only three of us. So really - a nice cabbage about tuppence - done us. Or whatever vegetables was in season - my mother 
a
lways bought. If it's only small portions, but you always had it. Like runner beans - you might get a spoonful of that, in those days. But - you got what - was going round the market. You see, there's runner beans, there was turnips. Onions. Onions used t
o be a penny a pound. You'd get a lot for a pound. A pound of onions. It's a different years of life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you wouldn't have any dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. Not if I can help it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 But they were around at that time were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
If you wanted something on the table like salt did you ask for it or just help yourself or did you have to wait for it to be passed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh my mother always served the meals up. Oh I - never - never asked for anything. Everything was served to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I was thinking of something like the salt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh, salt, no, no, it was always on the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You could just help yourself to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 mustn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 -t talk while eating. That was number one. Seco
ndly - you may - when you're finished your dinner and you wanted to get down - you've got to ask mum and dad if you can leave the table. And they'd say.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What would you do before you were old enough to eat at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well I - that was - say q
uick eaters, I was a quick eater, but - a slow eater now. But - I used to say when I knew mum and dad finished their - may I leave the table. Oh yes, you can. But when it was Sunday - I had to go to Sunday school, of course we had to - I had to get out a 
bit sharp, I'd say, mum can I leave the table? So she said, yes. And she - always left the Bible on there for me. And - - I - used to have to go to Sunday school - three to four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where would you eat before you were old enough to eat at the table, when 
you were very small? Who would help you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh I had to stop there 'til mum and dad was finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
When you were very young where would you sit, would you be sitting at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Oh yes. Always on - on the table. We had a big round 
table. The old fashioned one. Yes. Yes. And - we had to sit - I had to sit there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. No second helping. Only - rice. I used to like rice. My mother used to bake a rice - or a - egg custard, I used to like
 that. And - my father wasn't - fond of afters. But I used to have a bit - of backed custard, egg and - milk. Or rice. My mother used to have - afters. My father liked raw fruit. He used to like raw fruit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I suppose there was plenty of that around as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes. But - he always had - a plate of - fruit beside of his bed, when - he was going to bed. Especially blackcurrants. He loved blackcurrants. My mother used to cook 'em - and leave them there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So you had lots of good healthy food going all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - really - he worked one with the other as regards his food. You see. You can go a cabbage might last you - say for a day, might last you a bit more. You do it in bubble and squeak - of years ago. Fry it up. They used to. And - black
currants in those days when they first come out they was last end of the year, blackcurrants that my mother ever bought. Well they was only about fourpence a pound. That lasted is about - two days. Say a pound. Little and often. Little - and good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say your father would be working on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So when would you have the Christmas dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
About - three - three o'clock. You see, and he used to have a lay down and - that - used to - serve the coffee shops - but didn't go up to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Liverpool Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} station of a night, not Christmas Day. Only served the coffee shops - who - for the market, when it opens, that the people who - men from the market could go and have their - mug of tea, and their breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 The market was open on Christmas Day as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Some of them. Very few though. But the regular customers - they used to like to - go up there and - then my mother used to cook 'em - some used to have steak - for breakfast. Well a man wants it. About four o'clock in the morni
ng. 'Cos they opened very early, Spitalfields market. They did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Your mother used to cook, this was before she married your father was it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no, when she married my father. She worked in Spitalfields market before she married my father. Yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Can you remember any funeral in the family - in these years, can you remember what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Your grandfather or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh me father, I remember me father 'cos he died in 1939.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Can you remember in the years
 before 1918, can you remember like your grandfather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes. One, me grandfather Curle. He - died - it was near Christmas. And - dad come home, he said, dad's died, and we went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bow{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}Cemetery{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He got buried there. Bow cemetery, but that's about the only one I've said I've ever been to. My grandfather Curle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have carriages and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. I think there was three car - three carriages with the - black - velvets at the side, and they used to have feathers on top of the hea
rse. They used to Feathers. What they used to put in the horses head. There was a funeral on. Big feathers like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What was the purpose of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh well, that's how people wanted it you see, every - would say, well we want the feathers. Now y
ou know a hearse don't you? Well they're big, and the glass frame of the hearse - but on top, there was feathers. All done in with what do you call it, in silk, like to put in, on top. Feathers right across the hearse. And the horses used to wear them. Bu
t
 of the later years - well - but now they don't - believe in it. It's only cars, isn't it? But there is some of the - with the cars. They have the cars and they have the - velvets. What for, I think it's all show myself. The same as flowers, I don't belie
ve in flowers for a funeral.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You didn't have them when your grandfather died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - what - flowers? Oh yes. Oh yes. Plenty of flowers. That's always been the tradition of the English funerals, plenty of flowers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You don't agree with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
I - I - I don't agree with it. And I don't agree with getting buried. As regards of underneath the earth. I think cremations the best of anything. You finish your life, out - don't matter if you've been good or bad. So - to me I want to be cremated. Beca
use it's just as much as going under the ground.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was it very rough round here in the days before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Very very rough. Oh yes. Frightened to walk along here. Over there there was a pub. And her name was Mrs James. She was a Germa
n. And - in those days the Irish people was here a lot. She stood about that heighth, they go into her pub, and all of a sudden we can here from the Building in College - up you go. Out you go. They wouldn't go out. This she was my dear. She used to get h
o
ld of 'em and - throw 'em out, in the gutter. And they used to come and borrow money off of here. But - she was a good - a religious woman, she was. She used to go to St Judes with a little - cap, and a bead cloak, she used to like to go to Holy Communion
 and the church at night. Very nice she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you see many policemen around the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. Never seen a - one policeman round here - of a night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Why was that do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Oh was terrible, not one policeman. Young fellow - young
 boy about that heighth was tumbling over here last night - as I come - I said, get down sonny. You ought to see what he said to me. Swore. Shocking. I thought to myself, what parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you brought up to respect older people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. Even do today. I do. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were there many policemen around in the days before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How did they treat the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 There was plenty of people round - policemen round here - before 1918. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 How did they treat the people around here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Very nice. Oh yes, very respectable. Well there's a couple we knew come along here every night. Evening me. And - his name was Bert Goatley. His names were - was. And many a time - stand on the landing - used to throw me up
 a penny. When he was on duty. Oh plenty of people about during the - before 1918 war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Were you ever told if you were naughty, I'll call a policeman if you're naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes, I - I was reprimanded. Oh yes, my mother used to do that. But everything was left to my mother to do. My father - I loved my father. And my father never swore at me and never hit me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What did he think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well he didn't agree with it. Really. He wasn't a religious man. But a respected man like my grandfa
ther. And he took after his own - own father really, well I saw my own grandfather. He never had much of a temper, my father. No, never. But I can say I had good parents. We made the best of everything. My mother even knitted my socks when I was a kid. An
d make all my underclothes. She used to. 'Cos I can call back - with the help of myself, as she brought me up to a decent way. And my father was a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say your father was out until very late at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would your mother ever have any neighbours in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. No. 'Cos my mother was busy making - knitting socks for my father. You see, and - knitting - knitting - and also sewing for me. And if she had any cooking to do to save her the next day as regards her pastry, she used to make it up in the night.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 So she was busy around the house nearly all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh she was, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was your father ever interested in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, he couldn't. Not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Was he ever a member of any clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. Never belonged to a club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
What about things like insurance, was he ever a member of any insurance society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. He - no, but my father, he wasn't a man to go out once he'd finished work. He never used to get home here 'til half past - say about half past ten or eleven. Then my mother used to cook him a dinner. Come home with about sixteen quid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Where did you get the golden sovereigns from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh in those - before the first world war. You see. Bacon was fourpence ha'penny a pound. Back bacon. Butter - was about eightpence or tenpence a pound. Potatoes - was two pound a penny. Best was four pound for threepence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say you had a golden sovereign, your mother gave you that did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 We had golden sovereigns, my mother used to give me a golden sovereign.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 To go out and do the shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. But come back with about - sixteen bob.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Did your parents ever give you any pocket money when you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, my - father used to give me a penny a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of things would you spend that on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well get four caramels for a farthing. You could. Get - ha'porth of - jellies, in those days. And the farthing used to spend in caramels again 'cos we used to like 'em. Across the road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say your father used to talk about poli
tics and things, was he actually a member of the Liberal party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. He wasn't - he wasn't a - a - like leader or nothing. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 But he was a member of the Liberal organisation?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. He was only a Liberal in views - of a party. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did he actually ever join the Liberal group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no, no, he never done that. But his - policy was Liberal. As regards the voting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, I couldn't - I wasn't old enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Later on did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, well I used to be a Liberal. My mother and father was - Liberal, I was a Liberal but now the Labour party is in power now, that's the best policy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever belong to any other youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, well, Miss - Mary Hughes -
 she used to run this dialogue plays, and that, and we used to have a club once a week - beside there, you know - darts they used to have in those days, ludo, and - 'til about eight o'clock and then we had to come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were there any other organisations you were a member of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. I used to go to Tonby hall for Swedish drill - when I was a schoolgirl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you ever a member of anything like a Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Band of Hope? Yes, I used to go to Band of Hope, but I didn't belong - to the
 Band of Hope. Because - we was learnt you're not supposed to drink - in the Band of Hope. And - my mother said, well - the best thing is to leave it and - 'cos you don't know what's got to - when you grow up, what you're going to be like. That's why my m
um wouldn't let me be confirmed. 'Course a parent can't tell what their childrens going to be when they grow up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 She wouldn't let you be confirmed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. She said, you might take to the drink and - or be - do something wrong, she says apart from which, she said, as confirmation goes - that's why I don't want you to be confirmed. But you can get confirmed now as old as you are.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did your mother and father like to drink occasionally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Oh yes. But - they was really strict with me. In some ways.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were the pubs open on Sundays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. From twelve 'til two. And from seven 'til ten. The pubs. My father had a drink and my mother had a drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 On Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Sunday. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you take part in any sports while you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, they never had them - in those days - really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no. No. My mother always changed me into a clean pinafore. See what you're brought up to be - or try to be and that you - you can't get away from it. You see. As I told you that my mother used to make all my clothes. All underwear and my frocks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever have a bicycle or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No, I never had a bicycle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you have any pets at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. Dumb bells I 
used to have. Yes. For exercises. Light ones though, I was only a child. And my father used to say, well - keep your muscles going, used your dumb bells and I used to go to Tonby Hall and do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What other kind of things did they have in Tonby Hall 
to do besides Swedish Drill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh - used to - there used to be lectures there - there used to be big meetings there. I mean to say - a railway - you know, bit of a strike, and - politics meetings they used to have there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever go to any of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, well you couldn't - wasn't allowed to because - you come to take railways, it was only be men there. But you couldn't voice your opinion about them kind of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When you were young were you allowed to play with who you liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes. I could to a certain degree but - only the people that lived in the Building.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When you were at school were there any gangs at the school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Gangs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do you remember any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Who were always on their own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, oh no. Not in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you go on to any other school after you left Christchurch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No, I never went anywhere else. I left in 1912.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Can you remember your mother being ill before the ill
ness in '27? Can you remember whether she was ill at all when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
My step-mother, oh yes, we had some happy times really, I mean to say, we got on very well together, and - she looked after me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Can you remember her being ill though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No. No. That was really a - - only the flu once. And she was in bed for a week. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What would happen then, who would look after the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well, I - I - I've asked her. But of course she got up, but kept in the warmth, because with a coal fire there's warmth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Who would make the fires, would that be your father's job or would your mother do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What's that? The fire? Oh yes, my father used to do that. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would he ever help with things like washing up or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
No, well he never had the time being on the - milk round. He didn't know how to wash up. 'Til my mother showed him. Like my step-mother. And he - he learnt it. But when he started Shadwell police station - I forget what year that was, but he had to was
h up. You see, he didn't know how to wipe a cup. He never done anything. But he - he was - and he was good with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 making beds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 He used to do that as well did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
When he was at Shadwell. He - at home. He used to make my bed and his bed. Couldn't make a bed, couldn't do nothing before - well he was always at work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I suppose he had his work cut out doing the milk round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well certainly he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say your parents didn't have that many friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. They was always together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 They didn't have friends coming into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. No. They just lived for one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
People divide society into different social classes or groups in those days before 1918, did you think of one - some people belonging to one group and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You didn't really think of them in terms of groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. No. No, I can't say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
What kind of group for instance would you say that you belonged to in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What group? What before 1918? Well it wa
s only the church wasn't it? And the girls and that, we used to have a walk round. And - that's all we had. When I went to St Judes church, and we all had our pleasures in there, in the side where they have all these plays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Can you remember being brou
ght up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no. Well was all the one. Oh yes, all the one. All the one class. My mother wasn't snobbish. If she knew 'em and that, well you still be friends. It was a very very - friendly 
crowd - in College Buildings, years and years ago. Lovely. It was like one home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Who would be the most important people in the neighbourhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. To what doing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were there certain people of who you'd say, oh he's a real gentleman or 
she's a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well you don't get that now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I mean in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes, oh they'd say, oh she was very nice person. Yes. Her and her husband goes out together. And - her daughter goes out - with 'em. But - everybody was friendly, and
 even neighbours, if one speaks to another and say good morning or good night, they say it was a lovely family. One with the other, in families, that's how they used to be. Different of today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Can you remember whether there was anybody you were supposed to curtsey to?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh no. Curt - curtsey to you? No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 For you to curtsey to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no. No. No. Well we was the middle - middle class, you might say, or the poor class a little bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What group would you say that you belonged to then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well I wasn't the low class, say the middle class. I mean to say - to be in the middle class, well - you knew your manners. And you - very - tried to be kind to people, and help one another - in those days. But you cannot get no help of today. None wh
atsoever. I had the flu - and nobody come to me, only my friend. And Miss Wagstaffe used to come up to me. Years ago - they was - brothers and sisters and mothers and fathers. Helped one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to the middle class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes. Oh yes. Yes, my father and mother really. She - now you come to take when my father died in 1939 - there's a neighbour here, they're gone now - when I told 'em when my father died - Jewish people, Jewish people - they come in and
 they said, when you burying your father, Bella? I says - I don't know yet, not until tomorrow, see, on the Monday - died on the Sunday. Well believe me - but - they got everything on that table to eat, to come back from the funeral. And the young person 
lives up - well, she's fifty odd now, upstairs now - there's her two aunts. There was everything you could think of was on that table to eat. And they never - charged a penny. And - it was everything, and of course dad belonging - the police - down at - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Limmer Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 then - the men come home and everything was cleared. They ate up - and what I had to go to the funeral, and that, and there was nothing left. It was beautiful. But they never charged me a penny. And I'll never forget it. If only a couple of week
s back I spoke about it. They never charged - when you going to bury your father - father Bella? So I told 'em Thursday. There was everything there. There was salt beef, there was salmon, olives, cucumber - cheese. Everything you could - well - varieties 
you couldn't think of. But they done everything. Used their own cutlery, their own - crockery, and they washed up. They never charged me a penny. That's Jewish people. Never charged me a penny for a thing. And I've never forgotten it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do you think you
r father, when he was alive, in those days before 1918, do you think he saw himself - did he treat people of one group differently from another group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes, he always helped 'em. Oh yes. My father was a kind man. We wasn't a boisterous man and he h
ad - nearly - no temper. My mother had to do - all the smacking - what's to be done to me as a young girl, but my father never interfered. So I - I must say - that I can always look back - to know - that I had a good stepmother and a good - and a father. 
S
o I mustn't grumble in my life can I? My hardest time now is now. Because I mean to say, I'm not at work. But I get me pension. And I've got to manage. Things have gone up we know. I mean to say, this new money - to change a pound note, it don't seem much
 change out of it do you? Of today. But there - I suppose we get it a bit tight times at the end of the week but there you are, we have to manage. You've got to go without something. But I - I don't go without much. But I tell - I mustn't grumble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do y
ou remember, you say that you were the middle class group and that there were the poor group as well, did all the people in the poor group have the same standard of living do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Or do you think there were some better off than others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh no, was all on the same level really. I mean to say, in - any - anywhere you worked and that - there wasn't - all that money - so if you was in the trade you might - earn a bit more. You learnt a trade - of apprenticeship.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Do you think t
hat people who were craftsmen or trained apprentices and things like that, did they sort of think themselves different from people who had no trade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Yes, some of 'em. No. No. All on the level. No. No, all on the level. With the working class and people as you just said - was all on the level.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What kind of people went to church in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - those the regulars. Really they go more then than they do of today. I mean to say they was very nice people. I mean to say that Mrs Banyard, she
 went to St Judes. Mrs Wilmott, she used to go from the - who lived in the hay yard in Whitechapel next to Woolworths, she used to go to St Judes. But - they was all very nice and happy. We was all happy. But you can't say that of today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Who would be
 considered the most important people round here, like the vicar or somebody like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - he - the vicar of Spitalfields church at the moment, he's a very nice man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 But before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well - religion has altered hasn't it
 of today, but the services - was - thrown into you - to learn. These - they have the service in the police to see if you - do go to church. But when people don't often go to church - like myself - well - it's - new thing to me, 'cos they don't know if I'
m coming regular or not, you see. But it's a - different - they was more stricter, the vicars in the younger years than they are today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would the vicars be considered important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What about people like shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. 'Cos they used to go and all. Shopkeepers and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would shopkeepers be considered prominent members of the community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh church, yes. Yes. Oh yes. Now, you don't - of course you don't remember, I do. Now, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Commercial Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 here - there used to be a - a bread - shop there, name of Venables. It was there for years and years and years. As a kid, as I grew up they was still there. Now they used to go to church at St Judes. And it was nice - to go into the church and see all th
e
 old faces of round about. Used to be full. And Reverend Carter - he used to do a very nice service. And when it was Harvest Festival time - it was nice there and was better there. Because you got the fruit from the market, and the big pillows which suppo
rts the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}church{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Spitalfields{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 church - used to be decorated with all bunches of grapes. Funnels the bakers in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hambury Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - he used to give the big loaves for Harvest Festival. Used to give four. And - Spitalfields market used to give - all green vegetables, bags of potatoes, and - the fruit. Was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 gorgeous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
. The altar was set so nice - with the fruit, in Spitalfields church, that - well I did go - I - I haven't been to church for years but I went there Harvest Festival, and I felt better. In myself to thin
k, well - I should go, but I haven't been. But that church was packed with beautiful flowers. And the fruit - right up to the pillars was all grapes hanging, all the way round. Even to the Vicar's - what his name - chard - Chard. He used to wear his - use
d to have his reading - of the service - that was all done in - fruit. Grapes. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oranges{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Where he used to say the services from. But everywhere you looked near the alter was absolutely - you had to be careful 'cos you could go round and have a look after the
 service. And even the cross was all decorated up with beautiful flowers. It was really wonderful. But it was always the same at Spitalfields church, because all the fruit was given -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Can you remember any particular bonfire nights when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes. We used to have a bonfire in the yard. Big bonfire, up to two o'clock in the morning. And we used to have the little lighters, walking round the fire. Oh it was lovely it was. And some of the mothers used to make the tea. Say eleven o'clock
 at night. As a child, the mothers used to make the teas for just - all the children, we would be - lighters of the fireworks - didn't burn your hands, oh yes, happy days they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When you left school would your life change in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well it
 hasn't. I mean to say, I've lost me mother and father since I've left school, I just led me own - way of going on, with me parents. See? I never had no - only that one friend. And that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Before you left school if you went out anywhere were you e
xpected to be in at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Certain time, yes. Ten o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 What about when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well mother let me out 'til about - half past ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Would she went to know where you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 We were. Certainly. Yes, when you're 
about fourteen or fifteen girls - girls go astray don't they. Well they do. Oh she knew every - and I - I was very straight that way. I say, mum, I'm }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 going out}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 , I'll be home about ten or half past. All right She know - where I'm going. And I'll be home lat
e. Or otherwise I had to be in by ten. But for all that strictness of life of years ago - I'd rather have than than of - of today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Do you think that starting full time work changed your relationship with your parents in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did they sort of treat you more as an adult?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Well - I'll be truthful, my father always called me baby. Up 'til I was - I think I was twenty-five to thirty. And when my mother was ill - what happened - somebody came in and they said - for goodness sak
e - Mr Curle - don't say baby. She's a grown up person now. But he still stuck to it, in - baby, I was called his baby 'til he died. But the doctor says, well don't say that Mr Curle, because I've got a sister, she's years older than me and my parents cal
l
ed her baby. Yes, so that's how it goes on. That's how life goes on. You see, so - one with the other - you see - some - some people lives are different to another. You hear something, oh me mother went into the pub. Others'd stop at home. But as I said, 
I
'm speaking for meself about - about here years ago. They was neighbours. And - they looked on you neighbours and if you had - wasn't well, they used to come in and see to you - might give you a wash, give you something to eat. You see, but it's not that 
now. Though you don't expect it in this block now 'cos they're old people. I had the flu. Never come in to me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When you first started work did you give your money to your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. When I was able to earn - a little bit of a living, say a
bout - two pound - I used to give my mother twenty-two shillings, then I had the eighteen shillings for myself. Well I used to say - five shillings a week spending money - pleasure. And then I used to try and save a couple of shillings for me clothes. And
 then I used to say to mum - here you are, I've bought you a few sweets. That's how the money went you see. But - I never saved much, you couldn't. On two pound you could really, yes, well by - but there's things you wanted for your work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you still go to church and Sunday school after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You say you had this friend in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Victoria{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, where would you go to with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I don't go now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 I mean in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh well, there's - we generally used to g
o - go to church then 'til I knew here I used to go to church. But we don't - now and again we go to - where's that place - up the Hall. It's a soldiers place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Horse Guards Parade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes, that's right. Only now and again go there but I haven't been since.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Where would you go in the evenings? When you finished work, would you go out in the evenings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
Oh yes, I used to go dancing sometimes. Yes, I used to run dance at Tonby Hall. Run that for three years. You see, and then sometimes - I use
d to go out - up the West End. 'Course the fares was only about threepence then. Up there and back threepence, well that's only sixpence. Cup of tea was only tuppence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Were there ever any fairs or circuses around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Not round here. No. Not round here, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever bring this friend home from work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh - oh yes, she used to come up to me and I used to go to her. Oh yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 When you were still living at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh - oh yes, she used to come up to tea Sundays. But I'm more to her n
ow than she is to me. The number one fares are too dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 She lived in Victoria?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did she live in Victoria in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 No. She lived in Bow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 You told me about the Sheep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Oh yes. They used to come through here - about 
half past six in the morning, the sheep. They used to go right down - the Lane, to the bottom. Turn left, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Middlesex Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And they used to go over Aldgate and - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Middlesex Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Mansell Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And on the right, there was a slaughterhouse. That go thr
ough the sheep to be killed. And there used to be about two - or three big carts of the bullocks, and cows. To be killed. And then - they - they used to call it - Blood Alley, in those days. But - the slaughterhouse was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mansell Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Well there's a - 
a little further up the road near - the Minories, there used to be what they called - Blood Alley. And they used to - send the meat round there after it was killed, hung up to be sold. And they used to take it up Aldgate. From 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mansell Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to - where the
 - bus garage is now - that used to be all butchers shops there. Only butchers shops - and a pub. There was. And of course you got very good meat then, being fresh. The same as - Benny Woods. They used to have very nice meat there, in Aldgate there. And t
he Micarados, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 sweet stuff}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 
 shop, that used to be there, and there used to be a tripe shop, where they used to have the tripe done - in the slaughterhouse. Lovely corned beef they used to make. And - pressed beef, and all that. And sheeps heads. They used
 to cook 'em. Half a sheeps head - was sixpence. A whole one was tenpence. There was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5787931 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Did you ever have any muffin men or chestnut men, things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6560113 IC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843 Well you do on Sunday. Down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Petticoat Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And Saveloys now - they have saveloys and roll
s, down the Lane, and chestnuts. But the fruit in the Lane - was very cheap. Used to get a whole big bag like that a brown bag - with the name of the man who's selling in the Lane - and only cost you about - two bob. Huts. Tangerines. Bananas. Apples, pea
r
s, plums. About two shillings or half a crown. Yes. It was absolute - really nice it was. 'Course things was cheap. You couldn't afford too much so you buy half a pound. But the people had - say - earned a bit more money, they used to buy these big bags o
f fruit. But there was a man - oh - name of Nathan, his son was down there - the grandson's down there now. Always Christmas time he always give me a box of tangerines - there was about - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4197523\charrsid13393843 dozen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3430147\charrsid13393843  and a half in them. Well tangerines in those days used to be - 
ha'penny each. Only cost you about a shilling. But it was really lovely to have that then. And everything was cheap. That's why, in our days - it - it all a different generation. You know the hard times of prices are high, don't you. See, we knew when it 
w
as very cheap. So you had to make your money last. If a man earnt twenty-five shillings a week to thirty shillings a week - he earned a lot of money. He give practically all that to his wife. I mean to say, you come to take beer. You get half pint and tha
t
 - a man goes - say he went to a pub. He'd get a glass of ale - ordinary glass of ale, you get a roll and - butter, cheese and five Woodbines - for fivepence. He get penny change out of a sixpence. In those days. There was other things down the Lane, I me
a
n to say - I used to like - the faggots and the pease pudding - in Aldgate, Benny Woods. Go up there about eight o'clock, see all - the old thing going. The saveloys in, and pease pudding. Pease pudding was a penny. Also the - faggots was a penny. And on 
M
onday, washday, which my mother washed, that was her dinner for Monday. Faggots and pease pudding. Oh, it was love - well really - they was hard times. But they was happy days. I mean to say - shopkeepers are different of today. They don't want to serve y
o
u. Whether they want to serve you or not they don't care. Because they're getting the big prices - of today. But years ago he was a working man. Who had the shops, so he sold his goods at working man's prices. I mean to say, the food - now you come to tak
e jellied eels, went Southend yesterday. Cockles - not - yes, cockles, guess how much a pint?
